\subsection{Genetic yield improvements}

The full model which corrected for both the year of release and yield
erosion was estimated to have better out-of-sample predictive accuracy
compared to reduced models containing only one predictor. As estimated
by the best model, there is no conclusive evidence that the yields of
medium grain rice cultivars selected and released by CCRRF's breeding
program have, on average, increased over the last 30 years. The
estimated change in grain yield per year in the CCRRF's breeding
trials at the RES was estimated to be a negligible
\Sexpr{release_yr_coef} kg ha\tsups{-1} year\tsups{-1}, with both
small positive and negative trends within the credible interval (90\%
CI: \Sexpr{rel_CI[1]} -- \Sexpr{rel_CI[2]})
(Fig. \ref{fig:release}b.). Hence, the evidence here is consistent
with little to no increase in yield potential over the study
period. When yield erosion is not corrected for in the comparison
(i.e., omitted from the model), there is an apparent small increase
per year (approximately \Sexpr{only_release_coef} kg ha\tsups{-1}
year\tsups{-1}; 90\% CI \Sexpr{only_release_CI[1]} --
\Sexpr{only_release_CI[2]}) (Fig. \ref{fig:release}a.), though this
estimate ignores the confounding effect of yield erosion over time and
performed worse in out-of-sample predictive accuracy.

After correcting for the other variables, some cultivars are estimated
to have greater yield compared to the overall average. The marginal
estimate for the performance of a cultivar averaged over the
uncertainty in the other parameters in the model (i.e., the random
effect) shows three cultivars with higher than average yields:
\Sexpr{paste(gsub('M','M-',rev(row.names(id_est))[c(1,2,4)]),collapse=',')}
(Figs. \ref{fig:release} \& \ref{fig:ids_comp}). A fourth, M-209,
might also have higher than average yield, though the CI for M-209
overlaps with zero (Fig. \ref{fig:ids_comp}).

