\section{Discussion}

We conclude that yield erosion has decreased the yield of cultivars
released by the CCRRF over the last 30+ years. Biotic and abiotic
forces have been speculated to be responsible for this
yield erosion since the cultivar's genetics remain
``frozen'' at the time of selection but the conditions the cultivar
may experience over time are continuously changing \citep{Peng1998,
Peng2000, Peng2010}. The trend observed here is consistent with
previous reports of the erosion of genetic gains of cultivar IR8 at
IRRI \citep{Peng1998, Peng2000}, suggesting the
erosion of yield over time is a phenomenon that widely affects rice
breeding programs. This highlights both the need for maintenance
breeding and the difficulty of increasing genetic yield potential,
especially in systems such as CA where yield is approaching the
physiological limit \citep{espe16a}. Without maintenance breeding
continuously selecting cultivars well adapted to current conditions,
CA rice production systems are predicted to have lost an estimated
\Sexpr{round(yrs_coef * (-36/1000), 1)} Mg ha\tsups{-1} grain yield
over the study period.

Overall, we do not find conclusive evidence of increased genetic yield
potential in medium grain rice cultivars released by CCRRF's breeding
improvement program over the period \Sexpr{min(mod_data[,'year'])} to
\Sexpr{max(mod_data[,'year'])}. After correcting yield comparisons for
yield erosion over time, the estimated yield improvement spans from
\Sexpr{rel_CI[1]} -- \Sexpr{rel_CI[2]} kg ha\tsups{-1} year\tsups{-1}.
Even when the comparison is not corrected for yield erosion, the
estimated improvements over time (\Sexpr{only_release_coef} kg
ha\tsups{-1} year\tsups{-1}; Fig. \ref{fig:release}a.) are still much
less than previous estimates of 37 -- 60 kg ha\tsups{-1}
year\tsups{-1} \citep{Omar2014}. We conclude that the breeding program
has likely been maintaining but not substantially improving yield
potential in the face of changing biotic and abiotic pressures.

However, the goal of a breeding program is to not only maintain the
benchmark yield of the previous ``standard'' but to surpass it. Given
the estimated yield decreases over time, to hit an ambitious target of
0.5 Mg ha\tsups{-1} (approximately 5\%) increase in yield per release
(with roughly 4 -- 5 years between releases), a new cultivar needs to
yield an additional \Sexpr{round(yrs_coef*-4,-1)} --
\Sexpr{round(yrs_coef*-5,-1)} kg ha\tsups{-1} in side-by-side
comparison on top of the 0.5 Mg ha\tsups{-1} target improvement. Often
realized side-by-side yield improvements are closer to 2 -- 3\% per
release, in which case no absolute improvements are made beyond
maintenance. The evidence here is consistent with the latter situation
occurring in CA, further suggesting that the genetic yield potential
has not increased substantially in the last 30+ years
(Fig. \ref{fig:release}).  

